    {
      "id": "b5196c75_35e41829",
      "file_path": "cps-ri/src/main/java/org/onap/cps/spi/impl/CpsDataPersistenceServiceImpl.java",
      "patchset_number": 2,
      "line": 647,
      "message": "Incorrect, it's used by deleteListDataNode on line 672. The original behavior was to throw DataNodeNotFoundException if a list or list element with that xpath does not exist (though deleteListDataNode also has surprising behavior like allowing root xpath to be deleted). We should probably deprecate the list-specific API functions. But in the meantime, this change keeps the behavior exactly the same, as shown in the unit tests.",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 6742,
        "name": "Daniel Hanrahan",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "daniel.hanrahan@est.tech",
        "username": "danielhanrahan"
      },
      "updated": "2023-03-08 17:54:54.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "0cd90e1c_f6e09d9c",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "id": "029df763_6e97fb15",
      "file_path": "cps-ri/src/test/groovy/org/onap/cps/spi/performance/CpsDataPersistenceServiceDeletePerfTest.groovy",
      "patchset_number": 2,
      "line": 80,
      "message": "Not sure why exactly. But I think it is acceptable. See other test cases:\n- whole list deletion is 10x faster\n- list element deletion is 4x faster\n- deleting large node is 33% faster\nI think it's worth taking the hit here. This change essentially equalizes performance, so deleting 50 grandchildren (leaf nodes) takes roughly the same time now as deleting 50 list elements.",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 6742,
        "name": "Daniel Hanrahan",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "daniel.hanrahan@est.tech",
        "username": "danielhanrahan"
      },
      "updated": "2023-03-08 17:54:54.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "264a6cb6_86a3341a",
      "unresolved": true
    },
